# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Define state `dp[i][k]` the maximal coin value we can get using the first i piles of coins with total `k` coins taken.

We can see that `dp[i][k]` can be obtained by `dp[i-1][l] + prefixsum[i][k-l]`, where `l <= k`.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Can build a 1D dynamic programming table since the state  `dp[i][j]` only depends on `dp[i-1][<=j]`. We can reduce the space by building a DP table `dp[k+1]`, for each new piles we update the table from entry `dp[k]` back to `dp[0]` so that we don't ruin the state `dp[i-1][<j]`.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$O(2000k)$
The worst case is when there is 2000 coins evenly distributed in `n` piles. In that case, the cost to fill out each entry would be `2000/n` and there will be `nk` entries to be filled out. Hence the total time complexity is `O(2000/n*(nk) = 2000k)`, which is tolerable.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$O(k)$

# Code
```
int dp[2001];

class Solution {
public:
    int maxValueOfCoins(vector<vector<int>>& piles, int k) {
        // dp of taking first i piles with taking n coins 
        // dp[i][k] <- dp[i-1][l <= k] + prefsum[i][k-l]
        // total coins taken are less than 2000

        // to prefix sum
        for (auto & v: piles)
            for (int i = 1; i < v.size(); ++i)
                v[i] += v[i-1];

        // 1D dynamic programming
        int n = piles.size();
        dp[0] = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i <= k; ++i)
            dp[i] = INT_MIN;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            int m = piles[i].size();
            for (int j = k; j >= 0; --j) {
                for (int l = 1; l <= min(m, j); ++l)
                    dp[j] = max(dp[j], dp[j-l] + piles[i][l-1]);
            }
        }
        return dp[k];
    }
};
```

